<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="349" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1439,501,1285]" pageId="6" pageNumber="349">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,717,744]" pageId="6" pageNumber="349">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
All body parts dark testaceous, much darker than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Richard" authorityYear="1957" box="[941,1072,718,745]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Apion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="roudieri">
<emphasis box="[941,964,719,744]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="349">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[981,1072,718,744]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="349">roudieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, claws not evidently distinct in colour from tarsal segments (
<figureCitation box="[480,583,754,780]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1913,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,273,1891]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1435,273,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Habitus and rostrum shape: 1–3. Mascarapion roudieri:1) male, lateral view; 2) female head, lateral view; 3) female, dorsal view. 4–7. M. richardi: 4) male, dorsal view; 5) male head, dorsal view; 6) female head, dorsal view; 7) female head, lateral view. 8) M. roudieri, female head, dorsal view." pageId="6" pageNumber="349">Figs 4–7</figureCitation>
). Scales on elytra slightly longer and more piliform than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Richard" authorityYear="1957" box="[1257,1386,754,781]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Apion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="roudieri">
<emphasis box="[1257,1280,755,780]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="349">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1295,1386,754,780]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="349">roudieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, not as dense and numerous when aggregated in spots, often longer than width of elytral interval (
<figureCitation box="[1204,1288,790,816]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–18" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1898,1923]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,381,1876]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1435,381,1878]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 9–18. Pronotum and elytral base: 9) Mascarapion roudieri; 10) M. richardi. 11) M. roudieri, female, underside of rostrum, SEM micrograph (scale bar 0.2 mm). 12–14. Male pygidium: 12) M. richardi, dorsal view; 13) same, lateral view; 14) M. roudieri, posterodorsal view. 15) M. richardi, sternite 8. 16–17. M. roudieri, female: 16) ovipositor; 17) spermatheca. 18) M. roudieri, male, metathoracic wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3405039/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="349">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). Rostrum of similar length in both sexes, in male 0.98–1.09 × as long as pronotum and 2.58–2.76 × as long as its maximum width (
<figureCitation box="[230,297,861,888]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1913,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,273,1891]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1435,273,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Habitus and rostrum shape: 1–3. Mascarapion roudieri:1) male, lateral view; 2) female head, lateral view; 3) female, dorsal view. 4–7. M. richardi: 4) male, dorsal view; 5) male head, dorsal view; 6) female head, dorsal view; 7) female head, lateral view. 8) M. roudieri, female head, dorsal view." pageId="6" pageNumber="349">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
), in female 1.08–1.22 × as long as pronotum and 3.20–3.31 × as long as wide (
<figureCitation box="[1178,1246,862,889]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1913,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,273,1891]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1435,273,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Habitus and rostrum shape: 1–3. Mascarapion roudieri:1) male, lateral view; 2) female head, lateral view; 3) female, dorsal view. 4–7. M. richardi: 4) male, dorsal view; 5) male head, dorsal view; 6) female head, dorsal view; 7) female head, lateral view. 8) M. roudieri, female head, dorsal view." pageId="6" pageNumber="349">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
), thus in females much shorter than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Richard" authorityYear="1957" box="[390,519,898,925]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Apion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="roudieri">
<emphasis box="[390,413,899,924]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="349">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[428,519,898,924]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="349">roudieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In both sexes antennal insertion much closer to rostrum base than eye length (
<specimenCount box="[1408,1432,898,924]" pageId="6" pageNumber="349" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
: 0.64–0.85 ×, 
<specimenCount box="[299,322,935,961]" pageId="6" pageNumber="349" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
: 0.71–0.85 ×); in female scape shorter than maximum rostrum width (0.87–0.93 ×) and 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1315,1329,933,947]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="349">rd</superScript>
funicular segment barely elongate. Pronotum in male 1.27–1.51 ×, in female 1.50 × as wide as head. Elytra 1.73–1.85 × wider than pronotum, in male mid-length/base width 1.27–1.35, in female 1.49–1.52 × as long as wide. In male profemur slightly thinner than rostrum width (0.92–0.97), protibia weakly arched, 4.71–5.00 × as long as wide; in female protibia 0.96–1.00 as long as pronotum.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1439,501,1285]" pageId="6" pageNumber="349">
Male. Spiculum gastrale with apodeme longer than fork (
<figureCitation box="[862,949,1114,1140]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–30" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1721,1746]" captionTargetBox="[157,1422,422,1693]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1435,417,1701]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 19–30. Terminalia: 19–23. Tegmen: 19) M. roudieri, dorsal view; 20) same, lateral view; 21) M. richardi, dorsal view; 22) same, lateral view; 23) same, anterior view. 24, 25. Spiculum gastrale (sternite 9): 24) M. roudieri; 25) M. richardi. 26–29. Penis: 26) M. roudieri, dorsal view; 27) same, lateral view; 28) M. richardi, dorsal view; 29) same, lateral view. 30) M. roudieri, female, tergite 7." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3244742/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="349">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
). Tegminal plate with ventral layer lighter medially; sclerotisation of parameroid lobes not expanded to apical lobes; fenestrae with small, fully transparent areas (
<figureCitation box="[223,354,1186,1212]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–30" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1721,1746]" captionTargetBox="[157,1422,422,1693]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1435,417,1701]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 19–30. Terminalia: 19–23. Tegmen: 19) M. roudieri, dorsal view; 20) same, lateral view; 21) M. richardi, dorsal view; 22) same, lateral view; 23) same, anterior view. 24, 25. Spiculum gastrale (sternite 9): 24) M. roudieri; 25) M. richardi. 26–29. Penis: 26) M. roudieri, dorsal view; 27) same, lateral view; 28) M. richardi, dorsal view; 29) same, lateral view. 30) M. roudieri, female, tergite 7." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3244742/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="349">Figs 21, 22</figureCitation>
). Aedeagal apodemes 0.75 × as long as pedon; tectum wide, rounded apically; pedon about 3.4 × as long as wide; endophallus densely microspinose (
<figureCitation box="[737,868,1222,1248]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–30" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1721,1746]" captionTargetBox="[157,1422,422,1693]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1435,417,1701]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 19–30. Terminalia: 19–23. Tegmen: 19) M. roudieri, dorsal view; 20) same, lateral view; 21) M. richardi, dorsal view; 22) same, lateral view; 23) same, anterior view. 24, 25. Spiculum gastrale (sternite 9): 24) M. roudieri; 25) M. richardi. 26–29. Penis: 26) M. roudieri, dorsal view; 27) same, lateral view; 28) M. richardi, dorsal view; 29) same, lateral view. 30) M. roudieri, female, tergite 7." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3244742/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="349">Figs 28, 29</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
